(10640, 'Rhétorique de la propagande à Rome : trois exemples d’usage politique du lexique', 'titre_article', 6, '&lt;r2r:ml lang=&quot;fr&quot;&gt;&lt;p class=&quot;resume&quot; dir=&quot;ltr&quot;&gt;Comme on a pu le constater r&eacute;cemment dans la rh&eacute;torique des candidats &agrave; l&rsquo;&eacute;lection pr&eacute;sidentielle, la part du lexique est tr&egrave;s grande&nbsp;dans la construction d&rsquo;une propagande : C&eacute;sar, Tacite et Quinte-Curce en fournissent trois exemples dans l&rsquo;Antiquit&eacute; romaine, &agrave; travers l&rsquo;usage qu&rsquo;ils font de la polys&eacute;mie du mot &lt;em&gt;barbarus&lt;/em&gt;, &laquo;&nbsp;ennemi &eacute;tranger&nbsp;&raquo;. C&eacute;sar &eacute;tablit une distinction entre les barbares Gaulois et Belges, qu&rsquo;il pr&eacute;sente comme &laquo;&nbsp;incapables de vaincre&nbsp;&raquo; et qu&rsquo;il a donc l&eacute;gitimement conquis devant l&rsquo;ennemi germain ou breton, barbare &laquo;&nbsp;mena&ccedil;ant&nbsp;&raquo;. Tacite fait ressortir la valeur de Corbulon face aux Parthes dont il d&eacute;masque la faiblesse, par opposition &agrave; Paetus, qui, &agrave; cause de son incomp&eacute;tence, se laisse abuser par leur violence. Quant &agrave; Quinte-Curce, la rh&eacute;torique qu&rsquo;il pr&ecirc;te &agrave; Alexandre refl&egrave;te la propagande du conqu&eacute;rant, que l&rsquo;historien r&eacute;v&egrave;le comme telle en affirmant l&rsquo;&eacute;cart entre les Romains et les Barbares au lieu de l&rsquo;annihiler.&lt;/p&gt;&lt;/r2r:ml&gt;&lt;r2r:ml lang=&quot;en&quot;&gt;&lt;p class=&quot;abstract&quot; dir=&quot;ltr&quot;&gt;As one could recently note in the rhetoric of the candidates to the presidential election, the vocabulary is very important in the construction of propaganda : Caesar, Tacitus and Curtius Rufus provide three examples of this in Roman Antiquity through their use of the polysemic word &lt;em&gt;barbarus&lt;/em&gt;, &ldquo;foreign enemy&rdquo;. Caesar establishes a distinction between the Gallic and Belgian barbarians, whom he presents as &ldquo;unable to win&rdquo; and whom he thus legitimately conquered opposite to the German or Britton enemies, &ldquo;threatening&rdquo; barbarians. Tacitus emphasizes Corbulon&rsquo;s merit in front of the Parthians of whom he uncovers the weakness, in contrast with Paetus who is misled by their violence because of his incompetence. As for Curtius Rufus, the rhetoric he attributes to Alexander reflects the conqueror&rsquo;s propaganda that the historian shows as such by asserting the difference between the Romans and Barbarians instead of abolishing it. &lt;/p&gt;&lt;/r2r:ml&gt;;'),
