(10801, 'L’« objectivité » journalistique : droit des citoyens, devoir des journalistes ?', 'titre_article', 6, '&lt;r2r:ml lang=&quot;fr&quot;&gt;&lt;p class=&quot;resume&quot; dir=&quot;ltr&quot;&gt;Dans le cadre d&rsquo;une th&egrave;se doctorale en sciences de l&rsquo;information, de la communication et des m&eacute;dias portant sur le discours d&rsquo;information m&eacute;diatique et les confrontations arm&eacute;es, nous avons consacr&eacute; une partie de notre &eacute;tude &agrave; la question de l&rsquo;&laquo;&nbsp;objectivit&eacute;&nbsp;&raquo; journalistique. En effet, les professionnels de l&#039;information sont cens&eacute;s r&eacute;aliser leur travail informatif de fa&ccedil;on &amp;quot;objective&amp;quot;. Sur la base des travaux disponibles et des d&eacute;bats men&eacute;s depuis des d&eacute;cennies (p.ex. Tuchman, 1972), nous avons voulu savoir comment l&rsquo;objectivit&eacute; est-elle d&eacute;finie et pourquoi elle constitue un crit&egrave;re important pour juger le travail informatif des m&eacute;dias de masse. Cet article pr&eacute;sente les r&eacute;sultats de notre r&eacute;flexion.&lt;/p&gt;&lt;/r2r:ml&gt;&lt;r2r:ml lang=&quot;en&quot;&gt;&lt;p class=&quot;abstract&quot; dir=&quot;ltr&quot;&gt;&lt;strong&gt;Is the journalistic &ldquo;objectivity&rdquo; the right of a citizen and the obligation of a journalist?&lt;br /&gt;&lt;/strong&gt;Within the framework of a PhD on Science of information, communication and media dealing with the media information discourse and armed conflicts, we have focused part of our study on the issue related to journalistic &ldquo;objectivity&rdquo;. In this regard, it is normally expected that journalists carry out their job following certain principles of &ldquo;objectivity&rdquo;. Based on existing documentation and ongoing debate over the past decades (for example Tuchman, 1972), we would like to have a better understanding of how &ldquo;objectivity&rdquo; is defined and why it has become an important element in assessing the work of mass media in providing information. This article summarizes the results of our analysis. &lt;/p&gt;&lt;/r2r:ml&gt;;'),
(10802, 'Dynamique de l’identité européenne', 'titre_article', 6, '&lt;r2r:ml lang=&quot;en&quot;&gt;&lt;p class=&quot;abstract&quot; dir=&quot;ltr&quot;&gt;&lt;strong&gt;Dynamic in european identity&lt;br /&gt;&lt;/strong&gt;This study is a theorical investigation concerning European identity. The research context is social identity theory (SIT, Tajfel &amp;amp; Turner, 1986), self categorization theory (SCT, Turner, Oakes, Reicher &amp;amp; Wetherell, 1987) and their recent developments. We principally argue that transnational categories are more important to reinforce European entativity than geographical cognitive levels of inclusiveness generally considered. &lt;/p&gt;&lt;/r2r:ml&gt;;'),
(10803, 'Les aspects identitaires des biais de catégorisation sociale : le cas de la représentation de l’Europe', 'titre_article', 6, '&lt;r2r:ml lang=&quot;en&quot;&gt;&lt;p class=&quot;abstract&quot; dir=&quot;ltr&quot;&gt;&lt;strong&gt;The identity aspects of the biases of social categorisation: the case of the representation of Europe&lt;/strong&gt;&lt;br /&gt;The purpose of the current research study is to put forward the relevant identity dimensions within Europe thanks to the laws of social categorization. Starting from a system bringing French individuals to express the affective links which they perceive between Europeans of various nationalities, we obtain a representation of Europe opposing the western to the eastern countries on an axis and the &ldquo;sunny&rdquo; to the &ldquo;cold&rdquo; countries on a second axis. The correspondence to geographic reality is quite close, the correlations between the subjective and the geographical axes being &amp;gt; 0.67, and so, significant. Yet, the bias due to social categorisation (assimilation, contrast, discrimination) only appears for the East-West axis, whereas the situation on the North-South axis does not reveal a systematic distortion in the perception. So, it seems that belonging to the Western bloc is a part of the subjects&rsquo; identities since they treat this bloc as an endogroup, opposite to the exogroup constituted by the countries of the other bloc.&lt;/p&gt;&lt;/r2r:ml&gt;&lt;r2r:ml lang=&quot;fr&quot;&gt;&lt;p class=&quot;resume&quot; dir=&quot;ltr&quot;&gt;Le but de cette recherche est de mettre au jour, gr&acirc;ce aux lois de la cat&eacute;gorisation sociale, les dimensions identitaires pertinentes dans le cadre de l&rsquo;Europe.&nbsp;A partir d&rsquo;un dispositif amenant des sujets fran&ccedil;ais &agrave; exprimer les liens affectifs qu&rsquo;ils per&ccedil;oivent entre Europ&eacute;ens de diff&eacute;rentes nationalit&eacute;s, on obtient par AFC une repr&eacute;sentation de l&rsquo;Europe opposant les pays occidentaux aux pays orientaux sur un premier axe et les pays ensoleill&eacute;s aux pays froids sur un deuxi&egrave;me axe. La conformit&eacute; &agrave; la r&eacute;alit&eacute; g&eacute;ographique est importante, les corr&eacute;lations entre les axes subjectifs et les axes g&eacute;ographiques &eacute;tant sup&eacute;rieures &agrave; 0,67 et &eacute;tant significatives. Cependant, les biais dus &agrave; la cat&eacute;gorisation sociale (assimilation, contraste, discrimination) n&rsquo;apparaissent que pour l&rsquo;axe Est-Ouest, la situation sur l&rsquo;axe Nord-Sud n&rsquo;entra&icirc;nant pas de d&eacute;formation syst&eacute;matique dans la perception. Il semble donc que l&rsquo;appartenance au bloc occidental est constitutive de l&rsquo;identit&eacute; des sujets puisqu&rsquo;ils traitent ce bloc comme un endogroupe auquel s&rsquo;oppose l&rsquo;exogroupe constitu&eacute; par les pays de l&rsquo;autre bloc.&lt;/p&gt;&lt;/r2r:ml&gt;;'),
(10804, 'Perception de l’égalité sexuelle Europe : une construction géoculturelle et géopolitique', 'titre_article', 6, '&lt;r2r:ml lang=&quot;fr&quot;&gt;&lt;p class=&quot;resume&quot; dir=&quot;ltr&quot;&gt;La recherche suivante examine les ressorts de l&rsquo;&eacute;laboration des perceptions sur l&rsquo;&eacute;galit&eacute; sexuelle concernant 15 pays europ&eacute;ens avant l&rsquo;&eacute;largissement. Elle essaye de montrer que l&rsquo;&eacute;valuation de la situation propre &agrave; chaque pays serait influenc&eacute;e par les st&eacute;r&eacute;otypes g&eacute;oculturels et g&eacute;oculturels plut&ocirc;t que par la r&eacute;alit&eacute; et la connaissance des l&eacute;gislations et des pratiques sociales effectives.&lt;br /&gt;Pour tester cette hypoth&egrave;se, 139 participants &eacute;taient sollicit&eacute;s pour indiquer leur perception de l&rsquo;&eacute;tat des rapports intersexes dans les 15 pays consid&eacute;r&eacute;s. Les r&eacute;sultats enregistr&eacute;s valident cette pr&eacute;diction. Concr&egrave;tement, l&rsquo;analyse factorielle effectu&eacute;e fait appara&icirc;tre une double polarisation de la perception port&eacute;e sur les pays &eacute;tudi&eacute;s&nbsp;: d&rsquo;une part, une polarisation g&eacute;oculturelle entre le &nbsp;nord &eacute;galitariste et le sud non &eacute;galitariste et, d&rsquo;autre part, une polarisation g&eacute;opolitique opposant les pays &laquo;&nbsp;majeurs&nbsp;&raquo; plus &eacute;galitaristes et les pays &laquo;&nbsp;secondaires&nbsp;&raquo; qui le sont seraient moins.&lt;br /&gt;Les r&eacute;sultats globaux sont discut&eacute;s en termes de modalit&eacute;s de l&rsquo;&eacute;laboration des croyances et des st&eacute;r&eacute;otypes sociaux. &lt;/p&gt;&lt;/r2r:ml&gt;&lt;r2r:ml lang=&quot;en&quot;&gt;&lt;p class=&quot;abstract&quot; dir=&quot;ltr&quot;&gt;The following research examines the factors at work when dealing with gender equality phenomenon. Its aim is to show that the positive or negative assessment of the situation in each of the 15European countries should be influenced by geocultural and geopolitical stereotypes about these countries rather than on the reality of their current legislations and social practices.&lt;br /&gt;In order to test this hypothesis, 139 participants were asked to provide an evaluation / assessment of the nature of gender status in 15 European countries. The present analysis confirm the main hypothesis. More precisely, the factor analysis highlights a twofold polarization: a geocultural one (North versus South) and a geopolitical one (major countries versus peripheral ones). In the first case, it is assumed that the gender relations are more equal in the North than they are in the South. In the second case, this matter is looked at benevolently when these countries play a major part on the economic and political scene.&lt;br /&gt;The recorded results are discussed in terms of modalities of the emergence of beliefs and various social stereotypes &lt;/p&gt;&lt;/r2r:ml&gt;;'),
(10805, 'Normativité des choix sociométriques et différences socio dynamiques dans la représentation sociale des relations entre nations européennes', 'titre_article', 6, '&lt;r2r:ml lang=&quot;en&quot;&gt;&lt;p class=&quot;abstract&quot; dir=&quot;ltr&quot;&gt;&lt;strong&gt;Normativity effects in sociometric choices and sociodynamic differences in the social representations of relations between European nationalities.&lt;/strong&gt;&lt;br /&gt;Exploring sociometric choices between 39 different nationalities within Europe, we identified a social representation of relationships between these nations. These choices (made by one&rsquo;s own nationality and supposedly made by others) enabled us to verify and understand a sociocentrism effect as well as a normative effect within the choices made by three nations (a French sample, a Polish one and a Czech one).&lt;br /&gt;Within all samples, the subjects&rsquo; nation centralized the higher number of links with others (emitted choices and received ones). However, this sociocentrism has a quite different meaning for each of the three examined representations. Within the French representation, the French (n=317) consider they would receive more choices than others, and they emit fewer choices than they receive, in a selective way toward who is supposed to choose them. Within the Polish representation, the Poles (=169) also consider they would receive more choices, but they emit their choices especially toward the western nationalities. As regards the Czech representation, the Czech nationality (n=327) is the only one which emits more choices than it receives and especially toward the western nationalities too.&lt;br /&gt;Beyond this sociocentrism, a large consensus emerged: dominant nations were clearly identified as the most often chosen: Germany, England and other founder member nations of the European Community&hellip;. The choices of each sample was nearer this consensus than the other nationalities were supposed to be. The more a nationality was supposed to be near this consensus, the more it was likely to be chosen. A selected and valuable norm of choice emerged with which the members complied to choose their partners.&lt;/p&gt;&lt;/r2r:ml&gt;;'),
