(11553, 'Stéréotypes et identité de genre attribués à Marine Le Pen, présidente du Front National', 'titre_article', 6, '&lt;r2r:ml lang=&quot;fr&quot;&gt;&lt;p class=&quot;resume&quot; dir=&quot;ltr&quot;&gt;&lt;a id=&quot;elisabethdoutreupmfgrenoblefrbody&quot;&gt;&lt;/a&gt;&lt;a id=&quot;bkmelisabethdoutreupmfgrenoblefrbody&quot;&gt;&lt;/a&gt;Cette &eacute;tude s&#039;int&eacute;resse &agrave; la vision qu&#039;ont les citoyens de Marine Le Pen, leader politique de l&#039;extr&ecirc;me droite fran&ccedil;aise, pr&eacute;sidente du parti Front National (FN) et d&eacute;put&eacute;e europ&eacute;enne. Dans la continuit&eacute; des travaux de recherche men&eacute;s sur Christiane Taubira (Ailloud et Doutre, 2014), nous avons cherch&eacute; &agrave; recueillir les niveaux de chaleur et de comp&eacute;tence attribu&eacute;s &agrave; Marine Le Pen en utilisant le &lt;em&gt;Stereotype Content Model&lt;/em&gt;. De plus, nous avons cherch&eacute; &agrave; mesurer l&#039;identit&eacute; de genre per&ccedil;ue de la pr&eacute;sidente du FN &agrave; l&#039;aide du &lt;em&gt;Bem Sex Role Inventory&lt;/em&gt;. Les r&eacute;sultats furent analys&eacute;s via les regroupements de participants (&lt;em&gt;n&lt;/em&gt;&nbsp;=&nbsp;397) suivant&nbsp;: le genre et le positionnement politique. Il est apparu que les participants poss&egrave;dent une vision de Marine Le Pen comme &eacute;tant significativement plus comp&eacute;tente que chaleureuse et plus masculine que f&eacute;minine. Ces r&eacute;sultats confirment que Marine Le Pen est vue de mani&egrave;re plus positive par les personnes situ&eacute;es &agrave; l&#039;extr&ecirc;me droite de l&#039;&eacute;chiquier politique et, ce qui est int&eacute;ressant en terme de pr&eacute;diction de vote, les femmes semblent imaginer plus que les hommes la pr&eacute;sidente du FN comme poss&eacute;dant une identit&eacute; masculine forte, identit&eacute; attribu&eacute;e aux postes de pouvoir.&lt;/p&gt;&lt;/r2r:ml&gt;&lt;r2r:ml lang=&quot;en&quot;&gt;&lt;p class=&quot;abstract&quot; dir=&quot;ltr&quot;&gt;This study explore how citizens see Marine Le Pen, political leader of the french radical right wing, president of the National Front and Member of European Parliament. We asked to a sample of citizens (&lt;em&gt;n&lt;/em&gt;&nbsp;=&nbsp;397) to completed a questionnaire&nbsp;: First, we collected warmth and competence levels as seen by citizens concerning Marine Le Pen by using the Stereotype Content Model, already used for Hillary Clinton and Sarah Palin in the past. Thereafter, we gathered gender identity assigned to the president of the National Front by citizens using the Bem Sex Role Inventory, once used in order to evaluate charistmatic leaders on their perceived gender identity. We run analyses in regard to gender and political positioning of the participants. Results show that participants perceive Marine Le Pen as significantly more competent than warm and more masculine than feminine. In addition, a significant effect of political positioning on the Setereotype Content Model and the Bem Sex Role Inventory was found, along with a significant effect of participants gender on the Bem Sex Role Inventory. However, no interaction appears between independent variables. These results confirm the fact that radical right participants see Marine Le Pen more positively, and, which is interesting for predicting voting behavior, women more than men seem to figure the president of the National Front with a strong masculine gender identity, the kind of identity assigned to positions of power. We can interpret our findings as an expression for radical right people of an ingroup favoritism towards a politician whose they feel close in terms of political idelology. Differences concerning participants gender can also be explain by an ingroup favoritsim of women for Marine Le Pen, by assigning her a strong masculine identity and a weaker feminine identity, people imagining power with terms which have masculine connotation. This analysis of the results, along with the lack of interaction between indepedent variables, incite us to search for variables which enable us to develop a suitable, accurate and effective voting model.&lt;/p&gt;&lt;/r2r:ml&gt;;'),
